        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"> <placeName>Cleveland</placeName> <date>April 13th 5617&#8212;1851</date></p>
			<p>Rev &#38; Dr Friend</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">On the other page I forward<lb/> you some information&#8212;or rather as <del>I</del> we editors<lb/> were wont to term it&#8212;an item&#8212;which if<lb/> it meet your approbation you are at<lb/> liberty to insert in your valuable periodical.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I have been in receipt within the past<lb/> two weeks of two new Jewish journals one<lb/> a childish affair published in <placeName>N.Y</placeName> under<lb/> <persName>Mr Isaacs</persName> supervision and the other by<lb/> <persName>Julius Eckman</persName> of <placeName>San Francisco</placeName> called the<lb/> Gleaner a very indifferent affair in my<lb/> estimation I assure you&#44; and one which unless<lb/> I much mistake is destined to be short&#45;<lb/>&#45;lived. The establishment of a sterling weekly<lb/> journal devoted to the cause of our Faith<lb/> and the development of the intellectual<lb/> resources of the Hebrews of the <placeName>U. S</placeName> issued<lb/> and published at <placeName>N. Y</placeName> or <placeName>Phila</placeName> I am<lb/> quite confident would in due time<lb/> meet with abundant success and be<lb/> a source of profit and incalculable<lb/> benefit to both the proprietor and the<lb/> Jews of this Country. Such a journal<lb/> I looked for in the &#34;Advocate&#34; but as<lb/> yet it has not made its appearance</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>and respecting its fate I am yet in ignorance. I<lb/> am aware that the publication of such a journ<lb/>&#45;al as I have named requires the possession<lb/> of a large capital in order to fully &#38; widely es&#45;<lb/>&#45;tablish its reputation resorting to those collater<lb/>&#45;al means now made use of by every new en&#45;<lb/>&#45;terprise to bring its merits fully before the<lb/> public&#44; and besides the requisite capital indi&#45;<lb/>&#45;fatigable labor and the voluntary and continued<lb/> efforts of the editor &#38; contributors are necessary<lb/> &#38; indispensable to secure its success. Notwith&#45;<lb/>&#45;standing all this I believe sanguinely in the ulti&#45;<lb/>&#45;mate prosperity of the undertaking and hope<lb/> yet to see it carried out. should I be spared<lb/> to acquire <del>first</del> independence so far as the<lb/> pecuniary affairs of this world go&#8212;and my<lb/> love of literature still continue unabated<lb/> &#40;and like the ancient fount I think it will&#41;<lb/> I sometimes think it may be reasoned for<lb/> me to take the <sic>iniatry</sic> step or rather &#40;as<lb/> that has already been done so ably by you &#38; others&#41;<lb/> to second &#38; carry out those principles which<lb/> will ultimately place our nation or people<lb/> in that position the God of Nature &#38; <placeName>Israel</placeName> intended<lb/> they should hold. Permit me to assure you of my distin&#45;<lb/>&#45;guished &#38; most sincere regard and believe me your<lb/> friend most truly &#160;&#160;<persName role="author">B F. Peixotto</persName></p>
			<p><addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#44; Editor&#44; etc</p>
          
